Call me a conspiracy theorist, but is it really coincidence that Francisco de Zurbar√°n‚Äôs name appears last in the index of all art books? Ok, I know, it might have something to do with alphabetical order. But it also reflects the Spanish painter‚Äôs far-from-glorious reputation across the centuries.


Created with the express Counter Reformation purpose of stimulating religious faith, Zurbar√°n‚Äôs intense imagery of martyrs and saints was scorned in much of Northern Europe as too devoutly and dangerously Catholic. In 1853, the Telegraph letters pages were bursting with outrage when the National Gallery purchased his painting of a skull-caressing Saint Francis. ‚ÄúWhy on earth would we have something so black and repulsive in our national collection?‚Äù went one.


